parameters: Excuse me, are you Lord Toma?\n< Serena >

Yes, but... have you also come to
inquire about the Minotaur?\n< Monster Doctor >
Me too?\n< Serena >

No, while I'm not uninterested in the
creature known as the Minotaur, what I
want to know about now is the Orc.\n< Serena >

So you've come to learn about your
enemy. That's commendable.\n< Monster Doctor >

You adventurers are, after all, monster
exterminators. Yet, it can be said that
you know far too little about monsters.\n< Monster Doctor >

The fact that their eradication isn't
progressing is partly due to that, I'd
wager.\n< Monster Doctor >

I didn't intend to make such a grandiose
statement.\n< Serena >
It's simply for self-defense.\n< Serena >
Very well, very well.\n< Monster Doctor >

To protect oneself is of great
importance. How many there are who even
shun learning for the sake of self-
defense.\n< Monster Doctor >

Ignorance, my dear, is no different from
a slow suicide.\n< Monster Doctor >
To live well is to learn well.\n< Monster Doctor >
Let me give you this book.\n< Monster Doctor >
...?\n< Serena >

It activated. Is this some kind of
grimoire? How curious...\n< Serena >

That book borrows a bit of its
owner's... which means your... magical
power to operate.\n< Monster Doctor >
Open it and take a look inside.\n< Monster Doctor >

...Goblins... Orcs... the rest of the
pages are all blank.\n< Serena >
What is this?\n< Serena >

Mostly blank, how splendid. It means you
know next to nothing about monsters.\n< Monster Doctor >

...So, this book is linked to my
knowledge?\n< Serena >
Exactly. You catch on quickly.\n< Monster Doctor >

However, this won't prepare me for the
unknown, will it?\n< Serena >

What I need is not a diary but a
reference book. Practical knowledge. The
gimmick of this book is interesting,
but...\n< Serena >

...I apologize. That was rather impolite
of me to say to someone I've just met.\n< Serena >

By the way, I haven't introduced myself
yet. My name is Serena. Pleased to meet
you, Lord Toma.\n< Serena >
Ah, don't worry about it, not at all.\n< Monster Doctor >

A frank opinion is very welcome. There's
no mistake in what you say.\n< Monster Doctor >

Consider that book merely a token of our
acquaintance.\n< Monster Doctor >

Now, regarding the Orcs, you want to
know their weaknesses straight away,
don't you? Not their ecology.\n< Monster Doctor >

That's right. I don't have time for
lengthy lectures.\n< Serena >
Very well, very well.\n< Monster Doctor >

Then let's get straight to the point. Do
not engage Orcs in a head-on battle.\n< Monster Doctor >

You mustn't think you can withstand
their attacks. They're too strong for
that. And don't attempt to hit them
repeatedly. They're resilient and won't
flinch from trifles.\n< Monster Doctor >

So if you're going to do it, either
pummel them with powerful long-range
attacks or exploit openings to strike
and retreat repeatedly.\n< Monster Doctor >

Of course, the Orcs know their own
weaknesses, which is why they appear in
groups of two or three.\n< Monster Doctor >

Fight carefully without being greedy.
Magic attacks work well against them, so
you should have the advantage.\n< Monster Doctor >
You think my method of attack is magic?\n< Serena >

Isn't it? With those slender arms, you
can't possibly swing a sword or axe
around.\n< Monster Doctor >

Inevitably, your means of attack must be
magic.\n< Monster Doctor >
I see.\n< Serena >

That's about it. Was this information
helpful?\n< Monster Doctor >
Very much so, Lord Toma.\n< Serena >
It's Doctor.\n< Monster Doctor >
Huh?\n< Serena >

If you're going to address me, it should
be as Monster Doctor.\n< Monster Doctor >

It's a nickname given by the folks in
the countryside in jest, but I've grown
quite fond of it.\n< Monster Doctor >

Understood, Lord Monster Doctor. Your
advice has been very helpful. For my
gratitude...\n< Serena >

Coins are fine. It would be rather
embarrassing for me to charge a lecture
fee for such a trivial conversation.\n< Monster Doctor >

If you insist on giving thanks, then
just keep that book I gave you with
care.\n< Monster Doctor >

This is quite a puzzling arrangement. To
receive something as a form of
gratitude.\n< Serena >

The mere existence of that book in this
world will eventually become a value in
itself.\n< Monster Doctor >

So, well... if it's alright with you,
please show it to me sometime.\n< Monster Doctor >

...So you mean to say it's an experiment
to see what content will be recorded?\n< Serena >
That understanding isn't far off.\n< Monster Doctor >

...Well... I can understand that much.
Alright, I'll accept it.\n< Serena >
That's good. That's good.\n< Monster Doctor >

Indeed. Then, Lord Monster Doctor, until
we meet again.\n< Serena >

Quite an interesting girl. Good
qualities, good magical power, and good
looks.\n< Monster Doctor >
Truly "good".\n< Monster Doctor >

Even I think so, so for monsters, it
must be even more so.\n< Monster Doctor >

The compendium she will compile seems
like it will be unprecedented.\n< Monster Doctor >

...I'm looking forward to it, Serena-
kun.\n< Monster Doctor >

If you have any more questions about the
monsters, come see me again.\n< Monster Doctor >

As I was peering intently, our eyes met
with the doctor's. He seems a bit
uncomfortable.\n< Serena >
It's a book.\n< Serena >

The breeding habits of monsters. The
surface and the essence.\n< Serena >

Hmm. To be frank, it's a book on a
slightly disturbing topic. It's rare for
me, but I don't really feel like reading
it.\n< Serena >
It's a book.\n< Serena >

It's riddled with holes and hardly

The monster doctor seems a bit taken

It's wheat.\n< Serena >

It's a closet.\n< Serena >

Yeah.\n< Serena >
It's a bookshelf.\n< Serena >

Here, there's a mix of books not just
about monsters but also from the seven
liberal arts. Perhaps there's a slight
emphasis on astronomy- related texts.\n< Serena >
It's someone's letter.\n< Serena >
It's not nice to peek into it.\n< Serena >
